  <!-- Abstract -->
  <h2 class="section-h2" data-reveal>Abstract.</h2>
  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="80">
    There are several classification strategies available for evaluating when a bearing has failed.
    Bearing failure is a gradual process, and the question posed is whether or not the best
    classifier should also be allowed to change based on the fault's progression. Using measurements
    from the NASA IMS 2nd_test dataset (984 total files, Bearing 1 outer race fault), three
    classifiers — Random Forest (RF), Logistic Regression (LR), and SVM — were evaluated at two
    stages of degradation.
  </p>
  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="120">
    At the incipient stage, RF detected 27/56 fault cycles (48.2%) while LR detected only
    7/56 (12.5%) — a 3.9× difference. At the advanced stage, both converged to AUC = 1.000.
    Latency was measured using CPU cycle-counting on a real ESP32 (Xtensa LX6, 240 MHz): LR
    at 184 ns vs RF at 23.3 μs — a <strong style="color:#2540c0;">126× difference</strong>.
    SVM was disqualified after misclassifying faults at 96.5 μs due to FPU precision errors.
  </p>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- Key Technical Points -->
  <h2 class="section-h2" data-reveal>Key Technical Points.</h2>

  <div class="tech-grid" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="80">
    <div class="tech-card">
      <h3>Real Hardware Validation</h3>
      <p>Unlike prior simulations, this model was deployed and evaluated on a physical ESP32 using the <em>EloquentTinyML</em> library — not emulation.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="tech-card">
      <h3>Multi-Stage Fault Detection</h3>
      <p>An FDR-based method with statistical features (RMS, Kurtosis, Peak) segments bearing health into three states: Healthy, Incipient, and Advanced.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="tech-card">
      <h3>CPU-Cycle Latency Measurement</h3>
      <p>Inference time measured directly on the microcontroller. Random Forest: 23.3 μs (5,592 cycles). Logistic Regression: 184 ns (44 cycles). Ultra-efficient real-time monitoring.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="tech-card">
      <h3>Cascading Model Strategy</h3>
      <p>Adaptive scheme: Random Forest in healthy state → switches to ultra-lightweight Logistic Regression once fault detected. Maximizes energy efficiency.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

