  <!-- Cognitive Stage Transition -->
  <h2 class="section-h2" data-reveal>Cognitive Stage Transition.</h2>

  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="80">
    Through the Fisher Discriminant Ratio (FDR) metric, the system mathematically distinguishes
    when a defect is minor (Incipient) versus when it shows considerable mechanical degradation
    (Advanced). FDR analysis shows a <strong style="color:#2540c0;">5.89× separability increase</strong> from
    incipient to advanced stage.
  </p>
  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="120">
    Upon crossing this threshold, the system dynamically stops running the Random Forest (a
    moderate battery consumer) and switches exclusively to Logistic Regression to continue
    tracking the advanced fault at a much lower energy cost.
  </p>

  <!-- Stat callout -->
  <div class="callout" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="160">
    <div class="stat-highlight">126×</div>
    <p style="margin: 8px 0 0; font-size:15px; color:#534f46; line-height:1.55;">
      Faster inference — Logistic Regression (184 ns) vs Random Forest (23.3 μs)
      on the Xtensa LX6 at 240 MHz.
    </p>
  </div>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- Hardware Speedup -->
  <h2 class="section-h2" data-reveal>Production Hardware Speedup.</h2>

  <p class="prose" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="80">
    Demonstrating software improvements in PC emulation is trivial. In this work, we iterated
    by directly measuring CPU clock usage on the real Xtensa LX6 architecture.
  </p>

  <div class="callout" data-reveal data-reveal-delay="120">
    <p class="prose" style="margin:0; color:#534f46;">
      We avoided tools like <code class="inline-code">micros()</code> that inject overhead
      in C++, and instead read the native hardware cycle-counter registers directly to ensure
      nanosecond precision — mathematically validating why Logistic Regression represents the
      optimal choice for passively powered remote IoT.
    </p>
  </div>

